and Birkenstock avoid it.) Also, Amazon has its own incentives=E2=80=94its =
ultimate objective, of course, is owning search rather than purely selling =
fashion. So Saks will have a hard time convincing many of its partner brand=
s to consent to selling on Amazon unless the company can persuade LVMH to d=
o the same. As you know, that=E2=80=99s not going to happen. (On this, the =
Saks spokesperson said they=E2=80=99ll =E2=80=9Cshare more soon.=E2=80=9D)

Finally, Saks Global executives, themselves, are struggling. The same
people who are justifying the company=E2=80=99s new policies to brand partn=
ers are simultaneously fearing that their own jobs will become redundant un=
der the new regime. Meanwhile, brands are scrambling to reduce their depend=
ence on the Saks Neiman Marcus group, whether or not they have other option=
s. You have to wonder why chairman Richard Baker isn=E2=80=99t closing more=
